        "id": 5641
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-16T15:26:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hmm, how does the computed value relate to DOM construction?\n\nMy understanding is \"computed values\" are essentially properties resolved to absolute values that can be used for rendering.  E.g. percentage -\u003e absolute value.\n\nhttps://www.w3.org/TR/2008/REC-CSS2-20080411/cascade.html#computed-value\n\nSince there are cases where the same element is used in different DOM contexts (e.g. via \u003cuse\u003e), it seems that computed values cannot be resolved at construction time as they depend on the use context not just their parent context?\n\nTo fully support CSS semantics, I *think* we need a separate \"ComputedProperties\" primitive-type-only structure for inheritance cascading.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 25,
        "startChar": 51,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 16
      },
      "revId": "b856aef4f02af477a42f657716c9674718d50317",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1000d518_d5d3bd72",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 26,
      "author": {
        "id": 10818
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-16T16:24:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Inheritance of this sort never seems to be called out as something that happens at DOM construction time, but I\u0027m not sure how else to explain this example:\n\n    \u003csvg version\u003d\"1.1\" xmlns\u003d\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink\u003d\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"\u003e\n      \u003cg stop-color\u003d\"red\"\u003e\n        \u003clinearGradient id\u003d\"MyGradient1\" stop-color\u003d\"inherit\"\u003e\n          \u003cstop offset\u003d\"0\" stop-color\u003d\"green\" stop-opacity\u003d\"1\"/\u003e\n          \u003cstop offset\u003d\"1\" stop-color\u003d\"inherit\" stop-opacity\u003d\"1\"/\u003e\n        \u003c/linearGradient\u003e\n      \u003c/g\u003e\n      \u003cg stop-color\u003d\"blue\"\u003e\n        \u003crect fill\u003d\"url(#MyGradient1)\" width\u003d\"100\" height\u003d\"100\" x\u003d\"50\" y\u003d\"50\"/\u003e\n      \u003c/g\u003e\n    \u003c/svg\u003e\n\n(part of test pservers-grad-18-b)\n\nThe resulting rect is filled with a gradient from green to red, not green to blue as one might expect. It seems to me that in fact the computed value for the stop-color must be done at DOM construction time, even though the gradient element can be referenced in arbitrary other contexts. This is only because the stop-color attribute is not inheritable (\"Inherited: no\" in the spec).",
      "parentUuid": "3e7e708f_5431ea62",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 25,
        "startChar": 51,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 16
      },
      "revId": "b856aef4f02af477a42f657716c9674718d50317",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f4625041_b6e5efef",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 26,
      "author": {
        "id": 5641
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-16T20:30:52Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Ugh.  What we\u0027re missing is the equivalent of a layout pass to resolve these in tree order before rendering.\n\nDOM construction time only gets us so far because one can always go back and update these after parsing - then we won\u0027t be able to recalc correct values.\n\nCrazy thought: can we drop property inheritance from the DOM?  We\u0027d still support inheritance at parse time, but only explicit values after.  Not sure whether anybody cares about programmatic styling...",
      "parentUuid": "1000d518_d5d3bd72",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 25,
        "startChar": 51,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 16
      },
      "revId": "b856aef4f02af477a42f657716c9674718d50317",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6b101be6_0d1027ea",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 26,
      "author": {
        "id": 10818
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-16T20:39:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "One other idle thought I had: if we allow nodes to traverse the DOM hierarchy, properties set to \"inherit\" could at render-time traverse *up* the hierarchy and resolve as needed. In the above gradient example, the parent node of \u003clinearGradient\u003e always remains the \u003cg stop-color\u003d\"red\"\u003e element, so when we go to construct the SkPaint for the \u003crect\u003e, those stop colors would be resolved dynamically, so to speak. We\u0027d take a performance hit relative to the current scheme but I think it would solve this dilemma?\n\nThat said, I think it\u0027d be ok to drop it. If someone explicitly asks for the ability to manipulate styling and have it respect these inheritance rules, we can revisit then. Until then, it does seem fairly niche.",
      "parentUuid": "f4625041_b6e5efef",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 25,
        "startChar": 51,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 16
      },
      "revId": "b856aef4f02af477a42f657716c9674718d50317",
